Tom Bensari is a furniture maker, master woodworker and designer based in Wrocław, Poland.

He is the founder of Bensari Workshop, a woodworking studio and school, and Bensari Ébénistes, a brand focused on collectible furniture and limited series objects. Together, these two areas define his approach, where traditional craftsmanship and contemporary design operate as a single, coherent practice.

Bensari Workshop is a place where traditional woodworking is not preserved as a concept, but practiced daily as a method of work. The same space functions as a professional atelier and as an educational environment where these methods are taught through direct experience.

His work is rooted in traditional cabinetmaking techniques, including dovetail joinery, mortise and tenon construction and hammer veneering. These are not references to the past, but active tools used to design and build contemporary furniture.

Within Bensari Ébénistes, these techniques are developed further in the context of collectible design. Objects are created with a strong emphasis on material, proportion and construction, where every element serves both structural and spatial logic.

In addition to his studio work, Tom Bensari is actively involved in craft education. At Bensari Workshop he teaches woodworking courses focused on real processes: working with hand tools, understanding wood as a material and building complete objects. The goal is not to demonstrate techniques, but to develop the ability to work independently with material and form.

His work and writing have been published in Fine Woodworking, one of the leading international publications dedicated to traditional woodworking:
https://www.finewoodworking.com/author/tom-bensari

Through his writing, he translates workshop practice into a structured understanding of technique, showing the relationships between tools, material and design decisions.

Tom Bensari represents a contemporary approach to craftsmanship in which traditional skills are not separated from design, but form its foundation. His work challenges the perception of craft as nostalgia, positioning it instead as a precise, demanding and relevant way of working in the context of contemporary design.
